                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1188">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/5294.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé d’Affaires</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Extracts.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-10-20T21:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 20, 1912—9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Minister for Foreign Affairs informs me that the policy of this Government is to
                    do nothing for the present in a military way except to surround Vera Cruz and to
                    prevent escape of Diaz. He thought that every day of delay and of inaction on
                    the part of Diaz would strengthen the position of the Government and alienate
                    the people from the rebel movement. He assured me that no bombardment or other
                    fighting in Vera Cruz was in contemplation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schuyler.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
